To simulate ocean drift using the symbolic OPHI framework with your specified chemical agents — H₂O, NaCl, and CO₂ — we anchor into the marine Ω equation structure as established in the emission for symbolic marine ecosystems:

🧪 Simulation Setup: Ocean Drift via OPHI

We use the universal symbolic operator:

Ω = (state + bias) × α

⚙️ Variables Mapped:

H₂O: base solvent — represents the state baseline (hydration, heat capacity).

NaCl: ionic salinity bias — adds conductive drift and density modulation.

CO₂: climate-variable bias — affects pH, carbonate buffering, and temperature-driven equilibrium.

🧬 Symbolic Mapping
Component	OPHI Variable	Symbolic Role
H₂O	state_ocean	Solvent medium; SST (sea surface temperature), stratification
NaCl	bias_salinity	Ionic composition; alters current behavior and drift inertia
CO₂	bias_atmo	Atmospheric CO₂ as thermal + chemical pressure on ocean state
α	α_resonance	Resonance with seasonal cycles, gyres, lunar pulls
